Instructions on how to install an Ubuntu VM in Virtual Box
Install Virtualbox

Setting Up a Virtual Machine with Ubuntu to Host a Website

    1. Download Ubuntu Desktop:
        Download the latest version of Ubuntu Desktop from the official website.
        Save the file to a location you will remember (e.g., Desktop or Downloads folder).
        During the download, select both checkboxes for proprietary software and leave all other settings at their default.

    2. Install Ubuntu in VirtualBox:
        Follow the installation prompts and create your user account with a username and password.
        Complete the installation process and configure preferences as needed.

    3. Enable Copy and Paste Between Host and VM:

    Install VirtualBox Guest Additions:
        Go to the VirtualBox menu bar and select Devices > Insert Guest Additions CD Image.
        Open a terminal in Ubuntu and run the following commands:
			sudo apt update
			sudo apt upgrade -y
			sudo apt install -y build-essential dkms linux-headers-$(uname -r)
			sudo mount /dev/cdrom /mnt
			sudo /mnt/VBoxLinuxAdditions.run

		***Sometimes there are issues with mounting the CDROM, make sure that it is mounted then run the commands.***
		Shut down the VM.

	4. Configure Clipboard Sharing:

		In VirtualBox, go to the Settings of your VM.
		Navigate to General > Advanced.
		Set Shared Clipboard to Bidirectional.
		(Optional) Set Drag and Drop to Bidirectional as well.

	5. Update the Ubuntu VM After Restart:

		Restart the VM.
		Open the terminal and run:
			sudo apt update
			sudo apt upgrade -y
			***Restart if needed***

	***Hyper-V Full Screen instructions***
	sudo nano /etc/default/grub
	CHANGE: GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiert splash"
	TO: GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT="quiert splash video=hyperv_fb:1920x1080"
	SAVE FILE
	sudo update grub
	RESTART VM: init 6


